PROBLEM: run-ceo-review.ts (cron_restart: 0 */2 * * *) generated 99 sprint files with 53 pending tasks autonomously. The sprint queue grew from ~22 → 53 pending tasks across week-85 through week-100, burying product tasks (week-76) 47 tasks deep. This depletes API credits on swarm-generated tasks instead of product work.

FIX: Add a pending-task count check at the TOP of the main() function in scripts/run-ceo-review.ts. If total pending tasks across all week-*.json files exceeds MAX_PENDING_SPRINT_TASKS (default 10), log a warning and exit early WITHOUT triggering a new sprint.

IMPLEMENTATION:

1. Read scripts/run-ceo-review.ts lines 433-465 first (the main() function header + early-exit checks)

2. Add a new helper function ABOVE main():

```typescript
function countPendingSprintTasks(): number {
  const sprintDir = path.join(ROOT, 'sprints');
  try {
    const files = fs.readdirSync(sprintDir).filter(f => /^week-\d+\.json$/.test(f));
    let total = 0;
    for (const f of files) {
      try {
        const raw = fs.readFileSync(path.join(sprintDir, f), 'utf8');
        const parsed = JSON.parse(raw);
        const tasks = Array.isArray(parsed) ? parsed : (parsed.tasks ?? []);
        total += (tasks as { status?: string }[]).filter(t => t.status === 'pending').length;
      } catch { /* skip malformed files */ }
    }
    return total;
  } catch { return 0; }
}
```

3. In main(), after the LOCK_FILE check (around line 447) and BEFORE the state load, add:

```typescript
  // Sprint queue guard — don't generate new sprints if too many tasks are already pending
  const MAX_PENDING = parseInt(process.env.MAX_PENDING_SPRINT_TASKS ?? '10', 10);
  const currentPending = countPendingSprintTasks();
  if (currentPending >= MAX_PENDING && !FORCE) {
    console.log(`[ceo-review] Sprint queue guard: ${currentPending} pending tasks >= ${MAX_PENDING} max — skipping sprint generation`);
    fs.unlinkSync(LOCK_FILE); // release lock before exit
    return;
  }
```

The FORCE flag (--force CLI arg) bypasses the guard for manual overrides.

AFTER WRITING:
  Run npx tsc --noEmit 2>&1 | grep -v node_modules and confirm 0 new TypeScript errors.
  Do NOT restart ceo-review — it will pick up the change via git-autodeploy on next trigger.

Developer confirmed actual API response formats:

SINGLE ITEM: { success: true, data: { id, invoiceNumber, ... } }
LIST: { data: [...], meta: { total, limit, offset, hasMore } }

The frontend api-client.ts does fetchInvoices() -> InvoiceListResponse, then invoices/page.tsx does setInvoices(data.invoices). BUG: the key is data.data not data.invoices. This causes data.invoices === undefined -> setInvoices(undefined) -> invoices.length throws -> error boundary fires ('Something went wrong').

FIX 1 — Update InvoiceListResponse type in frontend/lib/api-client.ts:
  FROM: interface InvoiceListResponse { invoices: InvoiceListItem[]; }
  TO:   interface InvoiceListResponse { data: InvoiceListItem[]; meta: { total: number; limit: number; offset: number; hasMore: boolean; }; }

FIX 2 — Update invoices/page.tsx:
  FROM: setInvoices(data.invoices);
  TO:   setInvoices(data.data);

FIX 3 — InvoiceListItem: add optional fields actually returned by API: sellerName?, customerName?, customerEmail?, total?, subtotal?, taxAmount?, taxRate?, taxType?, taxCountry?, serviceDescription? (all string|number|null optional). invoiceNumber should be string (e.g. 'INV-002').

FIX 4 — Check handleResponse in api-client.ts. Single items are wrapped in { success, data }. If apiGet does NOT unwrap this, fetchInvoiceById, fetchDashboardStats etc. are also broken. Add conditional unwrapping: if response body has { success: true, data } shape, return body.data. But lists use { data: [...], meta: {...} } not { success, data }, so unwrap only when body.success === true. Simple guard: if (body && body.success === true && 'data' in body && !('meta' in body)) return body.data;

Files: frontend/lib/api-client.ts + frontend/app/invoices/page.tsx
After fix: Invoices page should load without error boundary.
